Psuedocode (Claude Generated)

<!-- System has 3 loops -->
1. Agent Beacon - Runs forever on the target
2. Server request - Reacts to agent and operator
3. Operator loop - Human tasks, reads results


<!-- Agent Beacon Loop -->
on start:
    id   = load_or_generate_identity()
    meta = collect_minimal_metadata()     # hostname, user, os — for the operator to identify the session
    register(id, meta)                     # one-time announce

loop forever:
    sleep(interval + random_jitter())      # never a fixed interval
    try:
        tasks = request_tasks(id)          # pull
        for task in tasks:
            result = execute(task)         # dispatch on task.type
            send_result(id, task.id, result)
    except NetworkError:
        backoff()                          # server down ≠ agent dies; retry later
        continue

Agent always initiates. Connection is outbound
Fixed timing is giveaway. Use random_jitter
execute is a dispatch table. Map task.type -> handler
Handler is "run shell command and capture output"

<!-- Server request handlers -->
register endpoint -> validate and create agent record, returns id
get_task(id) -> Lookup agent, last seen when -> pop qued tasks for the ID, mark them dispatched then returns
operater_enqueue(id,cmd) Validate, create task for agent

Two pieces of logic do most of the work:
Check-in updates liveness. Every get_tasks call refreshes last_seen. 
That single write is how you later tell live agents from dead ones — no separate heartbeat needed.
Tasks move through states, they aren't deleted. 
Popping a task means flipping queued → dispatched, not removing it. You keep the record so you can match the result back and show history.

queued ──(agent pulls)──► dispatched ──(result arrives)──► complete
   │                          │
   │                          └──(no result in N intervals)──► timed_out
   └──(operator cancels)──► cancelled


Agent session
gap = now - last_seen
if gap < interval * 3:        active
elif gap < interval * 10:     stale
else:                         dead


